        <section class="section">
            <h2>History of Chess Openings</h2>
            <p>Chess openings have evolved over centuries, with documented strategies and moves dating back to the earliest recorded games. The concept of opening theory began to take shape in the 15th century as players analyzed and documented their games.</p>
            <p>Notable players and theorists throughout history, such as Ruy López and François-André Danican Philidor, contributed to the development and popularization of various chess openings.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
            <h2>Famous Chess Openings</h2>
            <p>Here are some well-known chess openings:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Italian Game</strong>: A classic opening starting with 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bc4. It emphasizes control of the center and quick development.</li>
                <li><strong>Sicilian Defense</strong>: A sharp defense by Black against 1.e4, often leading to complex and dynamic positions.</li>
                <li><strong>Ruy López</strong>: Named after the 16th-century Spanish priest Ruy López de Segura, characterized by 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5.</li>
                <li><strong>Queen's Gambit</strong>: A popular opening where White sacrifices a pawn (1.d4 d5 2.c4) to gain control of the center.</li>
                <li><strong>King's Indian Defense</strong>: An aggressive defense by Black against 1.d4, aiming for counterplay and dynamic piece play.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>These openings are studied extensively and have been played by top-level chess players throughout history.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
